“We are close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will take Bolivia’s side – and that there would be no major changes if it did.
The UN Assembly, which has its seat in the Netherlands, does not have the power to hand over Chilean territory and has stipulated that it cannot determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The International Court of Justice’s ruling only six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And instead of advancing Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may have been a setback.
"The case of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
Morales's belligerent rhetoric has eliminated the remaining Chilean goodwill, she said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the discussions at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was abnormally fast.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end an era of 139 years of disagreements and gain benefits for both parties," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
