John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it has continued in 2018 with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which are also reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other local endeavours.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools seek to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can assemble and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will hit your heart.”
It is an important reminder that we cannot just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can see from the latest exam results this year that languages are the highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS’s 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received the grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as a subject choice at the same level as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) courses in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the reasons employers were unable to fill vacancies, 17% had to do with lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a huge advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start on the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
Speaking more languages, especially languages from developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, there are differences between schools in what languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to delivering a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills required to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the present time, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be truly important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and that must be reflected in the educations.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to Scotland’s youth.
I'm fine with the fair.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
