While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. But his speech seemed important as it did not unambiguously reject unilateral disarmament, as has previously been the case from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work “nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea has demanded a formal end to the Korean War, which took place in 1950-53, but the US has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to softening tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and expands the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose by coercion and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream come true among people who don’t know who we are.
