Ri did not mention plans for another summit between Kim and Trump, as the US leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in within the last five months, adding: "If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so locked down."
Nonetheless, the tone of Ris’ speech was very different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea’s missiles at the US mainland was inevitable, after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened "total destruction" of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for showing courage in terms of disarmament, but said that there is still much to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea disarmament.
