Harvard Students Take a Course on Getting Enough Sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture, where you study the whole night held up by large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world’s best university often do not know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has made the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the paper was finished, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why do I only get to know this now when I'm on the candidate?'
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleeping habits can improve one’s academic and sporting performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health field, says the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists, among other things, of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a dorm room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important good sleeping habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of the campus.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of the students right away.
But we think they have a right to know — just as one has a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride that is in taking an “allnighter” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain believe that you are starving, which is why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler organize the course last year when he took one of his courses on his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and had him work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next step will be for all graduates to be offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up. This can raise awareness of the harmful effects of the light from electronic monitors, which can move at the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
