What is the Global Citizens Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York hosts the Global Citizens Festival – an annual music festival with a very impressive array of artists and an equally impressive goal; to end the world’s poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizens Festival will receive tens of thousands of people on Central Park’s large lawn, where they can look forward to concerts with Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes. At the same time, the festival will raise awareness about the real goal, which is to end extreme poverty by 2030.
Started in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international interest organization that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concert attendees must perform a number of tasks or "actions". For example, do volunteering, write to a world leader, make a phone call or other meaningful action that can raise awareness about the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been now that they have 12 years to reach the goal?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert create real change, or is it just another case of so-called “clicktivism” – i.e. that people feel they are making a difference by signing a petition online or making a Twitter post?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its members aimed at various goals.
They believe these actions have spurred world leaders to set binding targets and policies equivalent to more than $37 billion, which is expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 goals and actions that had been achieved as a result of their actions, amounting to over $10 billion that had already been paid out or collected.
The group estimates that these funds have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
One of its main goals is The Power of Nutrition, which was started in the UK and is a collaboration between investors and people with a strong footprint. They strive to “help children live out their full potential” and pledge $35 million to alleviate nutritional problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the UK government, donors, other countries’ governments and world citizens like you, the social injustice of malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books,” Tracey Ullman, ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK government has now pledged funds to improve nutrition for mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 calls online. This project, Power of Nutrition, will help five million mothers and children with nutrition advice.
In response to one of the website’s frequently asked questions, “What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen wrote: "It will be a long and hard fight, and sometimes we will stumble and make mistakes.
But as with the civil rights movement and the movements against apartheid, it will succeed because we are stronger together.”
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are among the performers at this year’s festival in New York. Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will be hosts.
