Germany's new warship postponed again
The German fleet’s newest frigate should have been ready in 2014 to replace the Cold War warships, but the Germans have to wait at least another year due to technical problems and an escalating price, local media reports.
The deployment of the largest ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to be part of the fleet in 2014, but aftermath problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, which the fleet ordered back in 2007, will replace the aging frigates of the Bremen class.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a wide range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the latest frigates is a minor need for maintenance: it should be possible to keep the frigates away from the home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships – which are said to make Germany appear as an overseas force – will already be obsolete when deployed, Die Zeit writes.
The failed F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the fleet had delivered a ship back to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media mentioned a number of decisive "software and hardware failures" that rendered the warship unusable in combat situations.
Software failures were of particular importance, as the ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class must be controlled by a crew of 120 sailors – that is only half the crew of the older Bremen frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was far too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's ability for future updates.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the project, which includes training of the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an initial price of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
