The official said the problem has grown over time because the old ships were taken out of service without being replaced.
He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were ready to join the navy.
National Trust Snails to the Secret Life of Bats
New research from an area of the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the unique behaviour of flying mammals and will help in the work of future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from the Scottish National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at carefully selected locations in the area to record the bats’ activities throughout the season.
Data is also collected by NTS staff and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the sound recordings will reveal the frequencies of bat calls and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS Rob Dewar hopes that the findings reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help determine the benefits of habitat conservation efforts such as the establishment of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the UK has fallen drastically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect the owners and reduce their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials and attacks from pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because they hunt primarily at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the conservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect nests and sometimes carry out rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in the area around Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland’s bat species.
The area's caretaker, David Thompson, says it's an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a really good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
There’s a lot you don’t know about bats, so work here and elsewhere can help you understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and cubs, thereby risking the destruction of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how the populations evolve."
